WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.960
Most children don't even know what the traditional virtues are, courage, for example.

00:04.960 --> 00:09.160
These are virtues, these are things that you can actually cultivate as habits.

00:09.160 --> 00:12.920
And because education is supposed to be value neutral,

00:12.920 --> 00:17.720
and you know, it's left to people's religion or private conscience or family or something,

00:17.720 --> 00:24.280
most people don't get any religious teaching anymore at home or in a church or anywhere else.

00:24.280 --> 00:31.080
And some school teachers would be afraid to teach any of these things for fear of being accused

00:31.080 --> 00:36.600
of imposing their personal subjective values or ideology on children.

00:36.600 --> 00:40.720
So the result is there's a kind of moral vacuum.

00:40.720 --> 00:42.880
And it's very harmful, I think.

00:45.880 --> 00:48.880
Welcome to Rethinking Education.

00:49.880 --> 00:53.880
Education's critical friend.

00:55.880 --> 01:00.880
Rupert Sheldrake, welcome to the Rethinking Education podcast.

01:00.880 --> 01:02.880
Good to be with you.

01:02.880 --> 01:07.880
It's great to have you with me. It's making me smile, sort of, saying that out loud,

01:07.880 --> 01:11.880
because I've been very immersed in your books recently.

01:11.880 --> 01:17.880
I've read a few of them and listened to quite a few, and I've listened to quite a few of your podcasts

01:17.880 --> 01:19.880
and other podcasts that you've been on.

01:19.880 --> 01:22.880
And so it feels a little bit surreal to be speaking with you.

01:22.880 --> 01:26.880
So it's lovely to be able to spend some time.

01:26.880 --> 01:33.880
So I reached out because I've been, as I say, I've been reading lots of your work and really enjoying it.

01:33.880 --> 01:39.880
And there were a couple of books that you wrote quite recently, one called Science and Spiritual Practices

01:39.880 --> 01:42.880
and Ways to Go Beyond and Why They Work.

01:42.880 --> 01:46.880
And although they don't really speak directly to education,

01:46.880 --> 01:53.880
it feels to me like there are some sorts of educational implications to the things that you're writing about.

01:53.880 --> 02:00.880
And so I'm quite curious to see where this conversation goes, but yeah, we'll see what happens.

02:00.880 --> 02:04.880
But what I often like to do in this podcast is to get to know the guests,

02:04.880 --> 02:09.880
and obviously for our listeners and viewers to get to know you if they're not familiar with you.

02:09.880 --> 02:14.880
So could you please firstly just give a very sort of brief introduction to yourself

02:14.880 --> 02:18.880
for anybody who may not be aware of your work so far?

02:18.880 --> 02:26.880
I'm a biologist and I spent my, almost my entire career as a practicing scientist.

02:26.880 --> 02:31.880
I was educated at Cambridge to start with.

02:31.880 --> 02:34.880
I did history and philosophy of science at Harvard.

02:34.880 --> 02:40.880
Then I did a PhD in Plant Biochemistry at Cambridge and I was a Don and Director of Studies,

02:40.880 --> 02:44.880
a fellow of Clare College in Cambridge.

02:44.880 --> 02:49.880
So I had a kind of academic science training and practice.

02:49.880 --> 02:56.880
Then I felt I wanted a rather more adventurous life than just going on being a Don at Cambridge.

02:56.880 --> 03:00.880
And I had a job in India in an International Agricultural Institute,

03:00.880 --> 03:04.880
working on the improvement of chickpeas and pigeon peas.

03:04.880 --> 03:09.880
I was called the principal plant physiologist and I was running field experiments

03:09.880 --> 03:14.880
and working with a team on crop improvement plant breeding

03:14.880 --> 03:20.880
to improve agriculture for some of the poorest farmers in the world.

03:20.880 --> 03:25.880
When I was in India, I was got very interested in Indian traditions.

03:25.880 --> 03:28.880
I did yoga and meditation.

03:28.880 --> 03:33.880
I had a Sufi teacher for a while in Hyderabad, which is where I lived.

03:33.880 --> 03:39.880
And then one is at Cambridge, I had an idea called Morphic Resonance.

03:39.880 --> 03:42.880
I'll come back to that, the idea of memory and nature.

03:42.880 --> 03:44.880
I wanted to write a book on it.

03:44.880 --> 03:49.880
So I left my job for a while and lived two years in an ashram,

03:49.880 --> 03:56.880
a Christian Benedictine ashram on the bank of a sacred river in Tamil Nadu in South India.

03:56.880 --> 04:03.880
So I lived in this, I had a very happy time living in this, very simply in this community.

04:03.880 --> 04:08.880
Then I came back to England basically and worked part-time in India.

04:08.880 --> 04:15.880
My first book, A New Science of Life, came out in 1981, was quite controversial.

04:15.880 --> 04:19.880
Since then I've been doing research, mainly in biology,

04:19.880 --> 04:25.880
but also in rather underexplored areas of psychology, including parapsychology.

04:25.880 --> 04:28.880
I've written quite a number of books.

04:28.880 --> 04:32.880
I'm still very active in scientific research.

04:32.880 --> 04:37.880
I think six or seven papers last year in peer-reviewed scientific journals.

04:37.880 --> 04:39.880
I'm working on two or three more at the moment.

04:39.880 --> 04:44.880
So I'm very active in this area.

04:44.880 --> 04:48.880
Right, thank you. That's really interesting.

04:48.880 --> 04:52.880
So yeah, you're right. We will come back to that stuff later on.

04:52.880 --> 04:56.880
I think that it makes sense, in your case, to start at the beginning.

04:56.880 --> 05:01.880
And so I'd like to take you back to your own experience of school.

05:01.880 --> 05:06.880
Where did you go to school? What kind of school did you go to?

05:06.880 --> 05:11.880
I was born and bred in Newarkon Trent in Nottinghamshire.

05:11.880 --> 05:14.880
And my father was a pharmacist and a herbalist.

05:14.880 --> 05:21.880
And when I was born in 1942, and so soon after the war,

05:21.880 --> 05:25.880
he and a group of other parents set up an independent school,

05:25.880 --> 05:28.880
because they didn't think that the state one was very good,

05:28.880 --> 05:34.880
and started an independent day school, a primary school,

05:34.880 --> 05:38.880
which I went to called Highfields, called Newark Preparatory School.

05:38.880 --> 05:45.880
So I think I was well taught in sort of basic education there,

05:45.880 --> 05:48.880
sort of all the basic things you do at primary school.

05:48.880 --> 05:55.880
And then at the age of 10, when I've done the 11 plus and so on,

05:55.880 --> 06:00.880
but my parents sent me to a boarding prep school,

06:00.880 --> 06:03.880
which was the preparatory school for works on college,

06:03.880 --> 06:06.880
an independent school in Nottinghamshire.

06:07.880 --> 06:12.880
So I was at this prep school called Ranby House for three years,

06:12.880 --> 06:18.880
which being away from home at the age of 10 seemed normal at the time,

06:18.880 --> 06:21.880
but now I think of it as really rather odd.

06:21.880 --> 06:24.880
And then I was an all boys boarding school,

06:24.880 --> 06:28.880
works on college, 50 boys sleeping in the same room,

06:28.880 --> 06:33.880
in a big dormitory, somewhat military type discipline,

06:33.880 --> 06:39.880
corporal punishment, compulsory cadet force,

06:39.880 --> 06:44.880
compulsory rugby six days a week, whatever the weather.

06:44.880 --> 06:48.880
So it was a classic minor public school,

06:48.880 --> 06:55.880
authoritarian, disciplinarian, fagging, prefects,

06:55.880 --> 06:57.880
you know, all that sort of thing.

06:57.880 --> 06:59.880
And how did you find that?

06:59.880 --> 07:01.880
Because for lots of people now,

07:01.880 --> 07:04.880
that would sound just horrendously austere

07:04.880 --> 07:08.880
and that it might be considered to be borderline abusive.

07:08.880 --> 07:12.880
Yes, well, I just took it for granted.

07:12.880 --> 07:14.880
This is how it was.

07:14.880 --> 07:17.880
This is in the 1950s.

07:17.880 --> 07:20.880
I left school in 1959.

07:20.880 --> 07:24.880
And at the time, most schools had corporal punishment

07:24.880 --> 07:27.880
and boarding schools.

07:27.880 --> 07:29.880
Basically, it was soon after the war.

07:29.880 --> 07:33.880
Many of the masters, it was a boys-only school.

07:33.880 --> 07:36.880
Many of the masters had been in the war,

07:36.880 --> 07:40.880
you know, the army or the air force.

07:40.880 --> 07:45.880
And so there was definitely this post-war feeling about it

07:45.880 --> 07:48.880
and discipline was important, you know.

07:48.880 --> 07:53.880
And so, well, I didn't particularly like all that

07:53.880 --> 07:57.880
and it didn't suit me temperamentally very well.

07:57.880 --> 08:01.880
The emphasis in the school was on the highest prestige.

08:01.880 --> 08:04.880
Went to boys who were good at rugby and games

08:04.880 --> 08:07.880
and it was rather anti-intellectual, the atmosphere.

08:07.880 --> 08:09.880
I got very well taught, though,

08:09.880 --> 08:11.880
because most of the teachers,

08:11.880 --> 08:14.880
when they found someone who was actually interested

08:14.880 --> 08:18.880
in learning and curious and wanted to know more,

08:18.880 --> 08:20.880
which I did,

08:21.880 --> 08:27.880
they responded in a way that I felt had got a really good teaching

08:27.880 --> 08:29.880
from really good teachers.

08:29.880 --> 08:32.880
So I felt I was very well taught there.

08:32.880 --> 08:35.880
The social atmosphere of the school and stuff

08:35.880 --> 08:37.880
didn't suit me very well.

08:37.880 --> 08:40.880
You know, I wasn't very keen on compulsory rugby

08:40.880 --> 08:43.880
on days when it was, the ground was frozen.

08:43.880 --> 08:44.880
And when you were tackled,

08:44.880 --> 08:48.880
you sort of, the frozen earth cut into causing bleeding and stuff.

08:48.880 --> 08:50.880
I mean, all that stuff.

08:50.880 --> 08:52.880
It was designed to toughen us up.

08:52.880 --> 08:55.880
And into building they would have called it, hey.

08:55.880 --> 08:58.880
Yes, they called it character building, yes.

08:58.880 --> 09:00.880
And toughening us up.

09:00.880 --> 09:02.880
And I think it did toughen me up.

09:02.880 --> 09:05.880
You know, a lot of things in life after that

09:05.880 --> 09:08.880
seemed pretty mild by comparison with school.

09:10.880 --> 09:12.880
However, once I got,

09:12.880 --> 09:14.880
I won a scholarship to Cambridge

09:14.880 --> 09:16.880
and in those days,

09:16.880 --> 09:18.880
you had to stay on for a third year in the sixth form

09:18.880 --> 09:22.880
to do Cambridge scholarship or entrance exams.

09:22.880 --> 09:24.880
But as soon as I got that,

09:24.880 --> 09:28.880
I left and I got a job in London as a lab technician

09:28.880 --> 09:32.880
and like a gap here before I went to Cambridge.

09:32.880 --> 09:35.880
So, you know, I had a kind of classic education

09:35.880 --> 09:39.880
of that very old fashioned or boys type.

09:40.880 --> 09:41.880
Yes.

09:41.880 --> 09:43.880
And was it always going to be science for you?

09:43.880 --> 09:45.880
Was it science from a young age?

09:45.880 --> 09:46.880
Yes.

09:46.880 --> 09:49.880
My father was an amateur microscopist.

09:49.880 --> 09:51.880
He had a microscope lab at home.

09:51.880 --> 09:53.880
He taught me the names of plants.

09:53.880 --> 09:58.880
I kept lots of pets, animals, tortoises, pigeons,

09:58.880 --> 10:03.880
a rabbit, mice, hamster, a jack door.

10:03.880 --> 10:06.880
You know, I had a lot of animals,

10:06.880 --> 10:08.880
pets, budgerigars.

10:08.880 --> 10:10.880
We had a dog.

10:10.880 --> 10:13.880
So, I was very really into plants and animals.

10:13.880 --> 10:16.880
That's why I did biology.

10:16.880 --> 10:19.880
And then through my, actually,

10:19.880 --> 10:22.880
a kind of brought out kind of rebellious streak in me

10:22.880 --> 10:25.880
because I noticed that the first thing we did

10:25.880 --> 10:28.880
in biology classes was to kill things we were studying

10:28.880 --> 10:30.880
and then cut them up.

10:30.880 --> 10:34.880
There was a lot of dissection in those days in biology.

10:34.880 --> 10:36.880
And then the job I had in the lab,

10:36.880 --> 10:38.880
I was so keen to get experience.

10:38.880 --> 10:41.880
I wanted to be a scientist, lab experience.

10:41.880 --> 10:43.880
For my gap, nine months,

10:43.880 --> 10:45.880
I wrote round various drug companies saying,

10:45.880 --> 10:47.880
who got a job for a temporary lab technician?

10:47.880 --> 10:49.880
And one of them wrote back and said,

10:49.880 --> 10:51.880
yes, someone's just left.

10:51.880 --> 10:54.880
And so I got the job.

10:54.880 --> 10:57.880
And then I found I was the most junior technician

10:57.880 --> 11:00.880
in a vivisection facility.

11:00.880 --> 11:04.880
And it was my job to gas all the animals that survived

11:04.880 --> 11:08.880
the experimentation and toxicity tests at the end of every day.

11:08.880 --> 11:11.880
And so I was basically operating a gas oven

11:11.880 --> 11:14.880
for a kind of animal holocaust,

11:14.880 --> 11:18.880
which was appalling because I'd gone and loved animals.

11:18.880 --> 11:20.880
And so it set up a tension in me

11:20.880 --> 11:23.880
between kind of mechanistic science.

11:23.880 --> 11:25.880
Animals are just machines.

11:25.880 --> 11:27.880
Plants are just machines.

11:27.880 --> 11:30.880
We're just objectively dealing with mechanisms.

11:30.880 --> 11:32.880
And the fact I actually loved animals,

11:32.880 --> 11:34.880
that's why I was doing biology.

11:34.880 --> 11:36.880
So it made me much more questioning

11:36.880 --> 11:38.880
of what I was taught when I got to Cambridge

11:38.880 --> 11:40.880
than I might otherwise have been.

11:40.880 --> 11:42.880
Yeah, interesting.

11:42.880 --> 11:44.880
I had a very similar experience.

11:44.880 --> 11:46.880
I worked as a lab technician while I was at university.

11:46.880 --> 11:48.880
And it was in a very sort of non-scientific role,

11:48.880 --> 11:51.880
but it was a lab at UCL where...

11:51.880 --> 11:53.880
Actually, that was when I very first saw you

11:53.880 --> 11:57.880
because you did a talk at UCL back in the 90s.

11:57.880 --> 12:01.880
But yeah, I had to go and collect the animals

12:01.880 --> 12:05.880
from the animal house and dispose of their carcasses.

12:05.880 --> 12:08.880
And I used to see them on electrophysiology rigs,

12:08.880 --> 12:10.880
like a wrap with its sort of brain open

12:10.880 --> 12:12.880
and loads of wires going into it.

12:12.880 --> 12:14.880
And it's sort of anesthetized.

12:14.880 --> 12:17.880
And it's really just...

12:17.880 --> 12:20.880
I don't even know what word you could describe.

12:20.880 --> 12:23.880
It's sort of just grotesque.

12:23.880 --> 12:28.880
It's really an unpleasant thing to see happening.

12:28.880 --> 12:30.880
And in just such an everyday thing,

12:30.880 --> 12:34.880
you just go through dozens of animals a day in that way.

12:34.880 --> 12:37.880
Exactly. Well, you see, there's something about the...

12:37.880 --> 12:39.880
It was like a rite of passage.

12:39.880 --> 12:42.880
I mean, like medical students at university, you have to dissect.

12:42.880 --> 12:45.880
I think they still do it, dissect a human corpse.

12:45.880 --> 12:50.880
It forces you to become emotionally detached

12:50.880 --> 12:55.880
in a way that most biologists and medics

12:55.880 --> 12:57.880
have done something they've gone through,

12:57.880 --> 13:01.880
produces this kind of unnaturally detached attitude to life,

13:01.880 --> 13:06.880
which is necessary if you're going to have a mechanistic theory of life.

13:06.880 --> 13:08.880
Well, even if you're a non-mechanistic doctor,

13:08.880 --> 13:10.880
it's good to know the anatomy.

13:10.880 --> 13:14.880
And I suppose doing dissections is the best way of learning it.

13:14.880 --> 13:19.880
But anyway, for me, this was...

13:19.880 --> 13:21.880
It plays an important part.

13:21.880 --> 13:23.880
I liked the practical exams on the whole.

13:23.880 --> 13:24.880
I liked practical...

13:24.880 --> 13:28.880
I mean, practical, lab practicals in physics and chemistry very much,

13:28.880 --> 13:31.880
because I really enjoyed learning through doing.

13:31.880 --> 13:36.880
And there's less of that in science education now than there used to be.

13:36.880 --> 13:40.880
But learning through doing seems to be really, really important.

13:40.880 --> 13:42.880
And science was almost the only thing,

13:42.880 --> 13:44.880
apart from physical education,

13:44.880 --> 13:47.880
where you could learn through doing when I was at school.

13:47.880 --> 13:50.880
Yes. Yeah, absolutely.

13:50.880 --> 13:55.880
It's something that I resonate with as a former science teacher.

13:55.880 --> 13:58.880
We just had this brief conversation before we started recording.

13:58.880 --> 14:01.880
But yeah, the learning through doing...

14:01.880 --> 14:03.880
The kids would love practicals.

14:03.880 --> 14:04.880
They would always turn up to a lesson and say,

14:04.880 --> 14:06.880
oh, we're doing a practical today.

14:06.880 --> 14:10.880
And then your heart would think, well, you are doing a practical.

14:10.880 --> 14:14.880
But that practical involves following a series of five instructions.

14:14.880 --> 14:16.880
And there's no mystery in it.

14:16.880 --> 14:21.880
It's not really learning by experientially finding stuff out.

14:21.880 --> 14:23.880
It's just that you're following a preset procedure,

14:24.880 --> 14:26.880
and then you need to wash your equipment away

14:26.880 --> 14:29.880
and go and write it up in this pre-specified way.

14:29.880 --> 14:34.880
And so the learning by doing stuff really wasn't happening.

14:34.880 --> 14:36.880
Yeah, I agree.

14:36.880 --> 14:39.880
That's not happening to the extent that it should.

14:39.880 --> 14:42.880
Incidentally, the writing up thing,

14:42.880 --> 14:46.880
again, the traditional way of writing scientific papers,

14:46.880 --> 14:50.880
a test tube was taken, the passive voice.

14:51.880 --> 14:53.880
I was taught to do that.

14:53.880 --> 14:54.880
I learned how to do it.

14:54.880 --> 14:57.880
But when I got to Cambridge as writing real scientific papers,

14:57.880 --> 15:00.880
I found that most of my colleagues didn't do that anymore.

15:00.880 --> 15:02.880
It had gone out of fashion.

15:02.880 --> 15:06.880
But when my son Merlin, who is now a well-known mycologist,

15:06.880 --> 15:08.880
wrote a wonderful book called Entangled Life.

15:08.880 --> 15:09.880
Yes, Merlin.

15:09.880 --> 15:13.880
It's a school here in Hampstead at University College School.

15:13.880 --> 15:18.880
He wrote brilliant science reports when he was in primary school.

15:18.880 --> 15:20.880
He got to secondary school.

15:20.880 --> 15:21.880
They were all written.

15:21.880 --> 15:24.880
They actually said a test tube was taken.

15:24.880 --> 15:27.880
It was carefully heated with the substance in it,

15:27.880 --> 15:29.880
and then smelled.

15:29.880 --> 15:34.880
And so, you know, as if some disembodied being had smelled it.

15:34.880 --> 15:37.880
And so I said, Tim, why is your science report written

15:37.880 --> 15:41.880
in this incredibly artificial old-fashioned style?

15:41.880 --> 15:43.880
Because that's where you got to write science reports.

15:43.880 --> 15:47.880
And he showed me a specimen sheet his teacher had given them.

15:47.880 --> 15:49.880
And he learned it.

15:49.880 --> 15:52.880
And I then took this up with the science teacher

15:52.880 --> 15:54.880
and said, you don't really need to do this.

15:54.880 --> 15:56.880
You know, real scientists don't do this.

15:56.880 --> 15:58.880
And he didn't know that.

15:58.880 --> 16:02.880
He's a water relief and started teaching the active voice.

16:02.880 --> 16:05.880
I then did a survey of secondary schools in Britain

16:05.880 --> 16:09.880
of the heads of science, about 200 schools.

16:09.880 --> 16:13.880
And of them, about 30% of state schools

16:13.880 --> 16:16.880
were teaching enforcing the passive voice.

16:16.880 --> 16:19.880
About 60% of independent schools.

16:19.880 --> 16:22.880
And some state school teachers said, you know,

16:22.880 --> 16:25.880
it's hard enough to get my students to write anything at all.

16:25.880 --> 16:27.880
He said, so I can't force them to.

16:27.880 --> 16:30.880
Unfortunately, I can't force them to use the passive voice

16:30.880 --> 16:32.880
because they wouldn't understand what it is.

16:32.880 --> 16:37.880
He felt he was a failure for not enforcing the passive voice.

16:37.880 --> 16:40.880
And I showed this to the president of the Royal Society,

16:40.880 --> 16:44.880
Lord May, who was president at the time.

16:44.880 --> 16:45.880
He was appalled.

16:45.880 --> 16:48.880
He said, no one should be forced to write in the passive voice.

16:48.880 --> 16:49.880
He said, in this day and age,

16:49.880 --> 16:52.880
it's a sure hallmark of second grade science.

16:52.880 --> 16:55.880
And nature started editing scientific papers

16:55.880 --> 16:59.880
into the active voice at least 30 years ago.

16:59.880 --> 17:02.880
And almost all, I did a survey of scientific journals.

17:02.880 --> 17:06.880
I only found one out of 50 that insisted on the passive voice.

17:06.880 --> 17:09.880
And that was a minor and rather obscure journal.

17:09.880 --> 17:10.880
Isn't it interesting?

17:10.880 --> 17:12.880
And I've noticed a similar pattern.

17:12.880 --> 17:15.880
I now read more social science than natural science,

17:15.880 --> 17:18.880
but that same sort of format where people, for example,

17:18.880 --> 17:20.880
if they refer to their own previous work,

17:20.880 --> 17:24.880
they would say Manian 2019 wrote such and such as though Manian

17:24.880 --> 17:26.880
was somebody else rather than me.

17:26.880 --> 17:29.880
And it feels like you're trying to create this illusion

17:29.880 --> 17:33.880
that you are an impassive pair of eyeballs or consciousness

17:33.880 --> 17:37.880
that is just sort of objectively noting down reality

17:37.880 --> 17:41.880
and your own situated nature is just sort of erased out

17:41.880 --> 17:42.880
of it.

17:42.880 --> 17:45.880
And it just seems like it's a ludicrous conceit

17:45.880 --> 17:48.880
and that it's unhelpful, really.

17:48.880 --> 17:49.880
It is.

17:49.880 --> 17:50.880
It is a ludicrous conceit.

17:50.880 --> 17:53.880
And I mean, science is done by people.

17:53.880 --> 17:56.880
And an experiment is something you actively do.

17:56.880 --> 17:59.880
It's not something that unfolds in front of you,

17:59.880 --> 18:01.880
that passive observer looking at nature

