25:32.880 --> 25:35.880
Well, the mechanistic model which is still the dominant paradigm

25:35.880 --> 25:39.880
or model of reality that's taught in science and practiced in science

25:39.880 --> 25:46.880
is that nature is a machine that basically causes a by-pushing and pulling

25:46.880 --> 25:53.880
and there's no purpose in nature, no purpose in evolution.

25:53.880 --> 25:57.880
The mind's nothing but the brain, the body's a machine, the hearts a pump,

25:57.880 --> 26:01.880
the lungs are like bellows, the eyes a camera, like a camera.

26:01.880 --> 26:04.880
All these things are true as far as they go,

26:04.880 --> 26:09.880
but it just involves looking at everything through the lens of the machine metaphor.

26:09.880 --> 26:13.880
And it's only a metaphor, it's not a testable hypothesis.

26:13.880 --> 26:18.880
You couldn't do an experiment that would prove or refute the idea of nature as just a machine.

26:18.880 --> 26:23.880
It's just a metaphor, it's not a scientific hypothesis as such,

26:23.880 --> 26:27.880
but it's become deeply embedded ever since the 17th century.

26:27.880 --> 26:30.880
It's been the fundamental metaphor of science.

26:30.880 --> 26:33.880
But it's not the way nature actually is.

26:33.880 --> 26:36.880
And if you look at the way nature is, first of all,

26:36.880 --> 26:40.880
it's obvious that animals and plants aren't machines, they're living organisms.

26:40.880 --> 26:45.880
And they do have purposes, you know, if a dog's hungry it looks for food.

26:45.880 --> 26:53.880
And it's also clear that nature's organized in a series of levels.

26:53.880 --> 26:58.880
If you look at the small level then you have subatomic particles in atoms,

26:58.880 --> 27:00.880
nuclei and electrons.

27:00.880 --> 27:04.880
And then you have molecules which contain atoms in the molecule.

27:04.880 --> 27:07.880
And the molecule is more than the sum of the atoms.

27:07.880 --> 27:11.880
The water molecule is more than the sum of hydrogen and oxygen.

27:11.880 --> 27:15.880
And then you have crystals which are more than just the molecules.

27:15.880 --> 27:20.880
Ice is more, you know, especially snowflake with this beautiful six-fold symmetry,

27:20.880 --> 27:26.880
is more than just hydrogen and oxygen atoms or even more than just water molecules.

27:26.880 --> 27:32.880
And then when you get living cells, a cell is more than the proteins and DNA

27:32.880 --> 27:34.880
and lipids and things within it.

27:34.880 --> 27:38.880
And a tissue is more than just the cells because it's got more structure and organization

27:38.880 --> 27:40.880
and organs more than the tissues.

27:40.880 --> 27:43.880
An organism is more than the sum of its organs.

27:43.880 --> 27:48.880
They all work together harmoniously in an overall form with overall purpose.

27:48.880 --> 27:53.880
And then a group of organisms like a flock of birds or a hive of bees

27:53.880 --> 27:55.880
is more than just individual animals.

27:55.880 --> 27:58.880
It's the whole unit functions together.

27:58.880 --> 28:02.880
And then ecosystems and then planets and then solar systems.

28:02.880 --> 28:06.880
A solar system is more than just planets and the sun.

28:06.880 --> 28:08.880
They're all working together.

28:08.880 --> 28:12.880
And then a galaxy made of stars is more than just a bundle of solar systems.

28:12.880 --> 28:15.880
It has a structure, a pattern.

28:15.880 --> 28:20.880
So everywhere you look in nature there's levels of wholeness more than the sum of the parts.

28:20.880 --> 28:23.880
And each of the parts is a whole at its own level.

28:23.880 --> 28:26.880
So that's basically the holistic worldview.

28:26.880 --> 28:31.880
And there are certain properties that holes have, that all holes have at all levels.

28:31.880 --> 28:33.880
They're always more than the sum of the parts.

28:33.880 --> 28:38.880
And the wholeness somehow organizes and coordinates the parts.

28:38.880 --> 28:41.880
So they work together harmoniously.

28:41.880 --> 28:46.880
So that, I think, is the basic way nature is constituted.

28:46.880 --> 28:51.880
And when we look at it that way, then we can see physics deals with very small holes,

28:51.880 --> 28:58.880
atoms and subatomic particles, and basic forces like gravity and light.

28:58.880 --> 29:06.880
And also with very large things like cosmology, you know, the cosmos, galaxies, stars and stuff.

29:06.880 --> 29:14.880
Chemistry deals with sort of bigger holes than atoms and in molecules and ions and crystals and things.

29:15.880 --> 29:23.880
And biology deals with living holes from bacteria and microorganisms up to the most sophisticated animals.

29:23.880 --> 29:28.880
So I think when you look at it that way, it's easier to see how things fit together

29:28.880 --> 29:33.880
and it's easier to see how there's a common pattern to the way everything's organized.

29:33.880 --> 29:39.880
And we're used to it in, you know, when I was a child, I used to write those addresses, you know,

