30:42.880 --> 30:47.880
So can we, can you take us back to the origins of it? You said that you had the idea while you were at Cambridge.

30:47.880 --> 31:02.880
And what was the, what was the sort of the gap, if you like, in the mechanistic worldview that you thought that there's something that's missing here that you think that morphic resonance is, is an explanation as to how things are the way that they are.

31:02.880 --> 31:06.880
In Cambridge, I was working on plants and plant development.

31:06.880 --> 31:20.880
The reason I was working on plants is partly because I love plants, but also because I didn't want to spend my career guillotining rats and, and, and killing animals which research in zoology or medicine would have involved.

31:20.880 --> 31:26.880
So botany or plant biochemistry were for me much more attractive fields to go into.

31:26.880 --> 31:41.880
So I was working on how plant form develops. And I worked out, there's a, there's a hormone called auxin, AUXIN, indolacetic acid is its chemical nature, which is a key hormone in plant growth and development.

31:41.880 --> 31:58.880
And I worked out how AUXIN is made. And I discovered it was made by dying cells, that when cells die, the proteins break down, or tonicists, they have proteolytic enzymes, and the levels of free amino acids go up because the proteins are breaking down.

31:58.880 --> 32:09.880
And then just a amino acid destroying enzymes kick in and break those down. And one of the amino acids is tryptophan, it's present in animals and plants and bacteria.

32:09.880 --> 32:26.880
And when it's broken down, it's transaminated or deaminated to give indolpyruvic acid. And indolpyruvic acid breaks down spontaneously or by fairly non specific oxidases to give AUXIN, indolacetic acid.

32:26.880 --> 32:36.880
So dying cells make AUXIN. The main dying cells in plants are the wood cells, which become dead empty tubes. And as they differentiate, they produce AUXIN.

32:36.880 --> 32:46.880
And then it's transported from the shoots towards the roots via polar AUXIN transport system. And at Cambridge, I worked out how that works too with a colleague called Philip Rubrie.

32:46.880 --> 32:54.880
This is in textbooks now on polar AUXIN transport. We worked out the means by which it happened.

32:54.880 --> 33:05.880
So I was very pleased and excited. And we were ahead of anyone in animal studies. We knew what the key chemical was. We knew how it was transported. We knew the chemistry of its production.

33:05.880 --> 33:10.880
No one in animal development knew those kinds of things at the time.

33:11.880 --> 33:25.880
But then I realized that it's explained too much. All plants have AUXIN and polar AUXIN transport systems, you know, ferns, conifers, palms, cabbages, roses, you know, beach trees.

33:25.880 --> 33:33.880
And all parts of the plant have the same AUXIN production and transport system, the leaves, the flowers, the shoots, the roots.

33:33.880 --> 33:39.880
Yet the leaves are different from the flowers and a beach tree is different from an ash tree.

33:39.880 --> 33:46.880
And so this, which everyone said the molecular basis of development, everyone's hopes were pinned on AUXIN to explain it all.

33:46.880 --> 33:54.880
And I realized it just can't explain why they're different. It explains why they're similar, why there's a coordination of the tubes that conduct water,

33:54.880 --> 34:02.880
the right number of tubes to feed the growing leaves, etc. But it doesn't explain the specific form.

34:02.880 --> 34:10.880
Then I got interested in an idea put forward first in the 1920s of morphogenetic fields, form shaping fields,

34:10.880 --> 34:18.880
that there are fields that shape form like an invisible mould around a developing leaf that would cause it to be a leaf shape

34:18.880 --> 34:22.880
or around a developing petal that would cause it to be a petal shape.

34:22.880 --> 34:29.880
Like a magnetic field has invisible lines of force and shapes the space around it.

34:29.880 --> 34:36.880
The idea was that in plants and animals there are these form shaping fields which help to shape form.

34:36.880 --> 34:43.880
And I thought they're top down, the field causes it's not just bottom up molecules bumping into each other,

34:43.880 --> 34:54.880
somehow creating the form just from genes and proteins, which the reductionist approach still insists is the way forward.

34:54.880 --> 34:59.880
But there has to be a top down organizing system, these fields.

34:59.880 --> 35:03.880
So then the question is, how are these fields inherited?

35:03.880 --> 35:12.880
Because they can't be inherited by genes, genes just code for the sequence of amino acids and proteins or for switching on and off other genes.

35:12.880 --> 35:18.880
So I always thought genes were overrated. You know, I was teaching this stuff at Cambridge.

35:18.880 --> 35:24.880
Sorry to interrupt. I was quite sort of pleased to hear you say that because as a biology teacher,

35:24.880 --> 35:26.880
my degree was biology and psychology.

