35:38.880 --> 35:46.880
And protein synthesis, like you say, DNA just codes for amino acids which string together into proteins.

35:46.880 --> 35:55.880
And how does that describe a biological organism, organ systems.

35:55.880 --> 36:03.880
There seems to be like layers of organization that you were saying in this nested hierarchy, tissues, organs, organ systems, organisms,

36:03.880 --> 36:07.880
and then societal levels of that behavior and so on.

36:07.880 --> 36:14.880
There are just the genetic explanation that this is the brain of the cell and that this controls all of life.

36:14.880 --> 36:21.880
There's just lots and lots of leaps in that chain of explanation.

36:21.880 --> 36:28.880
Exactly. It doesn't make sense when you think it through, but most people still take it for granted.

36:28.880 --> 36:34.880
So anyway, when I was trying to think how could these be inherited, they couldn't be inherited through genes.

36:34.880 --> 36:44.880
And I didn't think they could be eternal mathematical equations because, you know, biology is all about evolution and changes with time.

36:44.880 --> 36:53.880
So some biologists, theoretical biologists who switch from being mathematicians, believe that everything is governed by eternal mathematical laws.

36:53.880 --> 37:00.880
And mathematicians tend to be Platonists. They believe that out there there's a kind of eternal mathematical realm on which everything depends.

37:00.880 --> 37:08.880
So I couldn't believe that dinosaurs had eternal dinosaur equations there at the moment of the Big Bang and still present today,

37:08.880 --> 37:13.880
but, you know, it was only a matter of accident or chance that dinosaurs actually existed.

37:13.880 --> 37:18.880
You know, this way of thinking that it's all about the maths didn't appeal to me.

37:18.880 --> 37:22.880
So then I thought, well, how could they be inherited?

37:22.880 --> 37:31.880
And at that stage I read a book by the French philosopher Henri Bergson called Matter and Memory, written in 1898 or 96,

37:31.880 --> 37:39.880
where he argued that memories are not stored in the brain and that there's a kind of causation, a memory causation, directly across time,

37:39.880 --> 37:42.880
not necessarily anything in between.

37:42.880 --> 37:46.880
And then I realized that if there was a kind of resonance across time,

37:46.880 --> 37:51.880
